and then from the birth of sociology in the nineteenth century through the twentieth century. While focusing on social thought, the book draws on many disciplines, including philosophy, anthropology, and political science. Joas and Knöbl demonstrate the profound difficulties most social thinkers--including liberals, socialists, and those intellectuals who could be regarded as the first sociologists--had in coming to terms with the phenomenon of war, the most obvious form of large-scale social violence. With only a few exceptions, these thinkers, who believed deeply in social progress, were unable to account for war because they regarded it as marginal or archaic, and on the verge of disappearing. This overly optimistic picture of the modern world persisted in social theory even in the twentieth century, as most sociologists and social theorists either ignored war and violence in their theoretical work or tried to explain it away. The failure of the social sciences and especially sociology to understand war, Joas and Knöbl argue, must be seen as one of the greatest weaknesses of disciplines that claim to give a convincing diagnosis of our times.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aPHILOSOPHYvGeneral. 0aPOLITICAL SCIENCEvPeace. 0aSociologyxHistoryx19th century. 0aSociologyxHistoryx20th century. 0aSociologyxHistoryy19th century. 0aSociologyxHistoryy20th century. 0aWar and society. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Violence in Society.2bisacsh  aAmerican sociology.  aAuguste Comte.  aCarl Schmitt.  aCarl von Clausewitz.  aFirst World War.  aGermany.  aHans Speier.  aHerbert Spencer.  aImmanuel Kant.  aJames Mill.  aJean-Jacques Rousseau.  aJeremy Bentham.  aJohn Stuart Mill.  aMarxism.  aMichael Doyle.  aMichel Foucault.  aMontesquieu.  aNapoleonic Wars.  aOtto Hintze.  aRoger C